entry.title: [wptrunner] Run tests in a subprocess for `--use-upstream-wpt`
entry.content:
`--use-upstream-wpt` is unreliable because it relies on path hacking

to (re)load modules at runtime. This can be accomplished more robustly

by running tests in a fresh interpreter with PYTHONPATH pointing to the

`wpt/tools` to use. This eliminates the possibility that `blinkpy`

transitively imports a `wpt*` module that will be invalidated later.



When invoking the subprocess, the `--use-upstream-wpt` flag is stripped

away, but the `WPTAdapter` can still dynamically detect whether it's

running with Chromium-vended WPT.



Fixed: 1473716

entry.title: Revert "[view-transition] Stop BrowserCompositorMac from calling WasShown while"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 8c4a1b3b564495c2e884b6bcb1f053a9afb4fe25.



Reason for revert: Introduced crbug.com/1484982



Original change's description:

> [view-transition] Stop BrowserCompositorMac from calling WasShown while

> hidden

>

> Calling DelegatedFrameHost::WasShown() while hidden will assign

> `first_local_surface_id_after_navigation_` with the LocalSurfaceId

> of `BrowserCompositorMac`. This LocalSurfaceId is considered

> stale for BFCache restoration with ViewTransition because such

> restoration will have customized primary and fallback SurfaceIds.

>

> When the fallback content timer is up, the stale value of

> `first_local_surface_id_after_navigation_` will be used to reset the

> fallback SurfaceId, which confuses Viz, causing a white screen.

>

> What this CL means:

> - As long as we are hidden: HasNoCompositor.

> - `SetParentUiLayer` used to be always "successful" because even though

> we are hidden, we use UseParentLayerCompositor to represent the state.

> With this CL, `SetParentUiLayer` won't re-parent `root_layer_` if we

> are hidden. `root_layer_` will be re-parented next time we become

> visible (HasNoCompositor->UseParentLayerCompositor).

>

entry.title: Changes hard crashes to DCHECKs for DevTools histograms
entry.content:
DevTools histogram reports would trigger hard crashes when out-of-range values were transmitted to the embedder from the front-end side. This doesn't really make a lot of sense; while it is desirable to have some insight to failing or improperly-ranged histograms, having a hard crash that occurs in all cases doesn't make a lot of sense because the histogram isn't something that can necessarily be controlled by the customer.



This change handles the count- and enumerated histogram types with the

following behavior:



- for both, we will DCHECK if compiled with DCHECKs enabled

- if DCHECKs are off:

- for count-type, we clamp to the client-specified acceptable range

- for enumerated-type, we skip recording the histogram if it's out of the acceptable range

entry.title: [Extensions] Disable SW dispatch stopping test for flakiness.
entry.content:
This test is proven to be flaky in test history

(https://luci-milo.appspot.com/ui/p/chromium/test-search).



The cause is that the content::StopServiceWorkerForScope(...) call sends

an async IPC to the renderer. This IPC sometimes completes before we

call ASSERT_TRUE(content::CheckServiceWorkerIsStopping(...)). The assert

then fails because the ServiceWorkerVersion has been destroyed as part

of that IPC completing and the call returns false.



Curiously per test history this started happening on Sep 13th, but I

don't believe any CL necessarily caused this.



There isn't an obvious solution to this, so disabling for now since the

behavior changes we're initially making at least aren't changing how we

respond to a stopping worker.

entry.title: Deflake MediaStreamTrack-video-stats.https.html.
entry.content:
A test was recently added which asserts that frames are frozen during a

task execution cycle. But it also asserted that after 100 ms and one

task execution cycle later, the frame counter would have incremented.



This is a reasonable assumption on a fast machine, but the WPT waterfall

can be really slow in which case no frame is produced in 100 ms and the

entry.title: Portals: Cancel drag-drop in predecessor before activation
entry.content:
We have existing drag-drop checks that prevent data from a

cross-site subframe from being transferred to the main frame, but

these break with portal activation. With portal activation we have two

problems:



1) Portal activation causes a switch in WebContents, and we currently

don't restrict drag and drops across WebContents (as dragging

across tabs is considered to be sufficient user-intent). However,

in this case, portals are within the same tab, and allowing a

cross-origin drag-and-drop across portal activation has the

same security risks outlined in https://crbug.com/59081 and

https://crbug.com/1264873.



2) Portal activation, adoption and reactivation can result in the

WebContentsViewAura being reset and recreated, so the |drag_start_|

field will be reset. We can have a portal being activated, the

predecessor being adopted, and then reactivated, all while a

drag-drop is active, and the resulting drop's checks will be

bypassed (within the same page) as |drag_start_| is reset and is

now absl::nullopt [1].



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/web_contents/web_contents_view_aura.cc;l=855;drc=c2cca37e05cb5b20019a27406714d1954194c2d4



To fix this, we explicitly cancel a drag-drop before activating a

portal. This disallows a drag-drop for persisting across portal

activation. The predecessor page becomes a portal and doesn't allow

input events at that point, and drag and drop failing shouldn't be unexpected behaviour.



Note: This only fixes the issue on Aura; but this likely needs a fix

for Mac as well, which will be in a follow up.

ApplyAddressFixesAndCleanups and ApplyCardFixesAndCleanups has multiple

call sites.

[1] From PersonalDataManagerCleaner::CleanupDataAndNotifyPersonalDataObservers

The call from [2] should happen if the user is syncing and have enabled the type in sync-the-feature mode or if the user enabled the relevant user selectable in the sync-the-transport mode.



The call from [1] should happen in all the other cases where the user

is not syncing at all or the user has not enabled the type.



Prior to this CL, there would be calls from both [1] and [2] to the

ApplyAddressFixesAndCleanups in sync-the-transport mode when the user

would have enabled the user selectable type as

`sync_service_->IsSyncFeatureEnabled()` would return false in this case.

This CL ensures that in this case, the call happens from only [2].

entry.title: Wait 500ms before retrying to restore the context
entry.content:
In case of failure to restore the context, the

CanvasRenderingContext2D::TryRestoreContextEvent method was retrying

right away, by calling itself recursively. If the function has just

failed, there is no reason it should succeed by merely calling it once

more.

entry.title: Use SEQUENCE_CHECKER in ResourceLoadInfoNotifierWrapper
entry.content:
Currently ResourceLoadInfoNotifierWrapper uses a THREAD_CHECKER to

ensure that all member methods are called from a same single thread.

This is intended to protect `resource_load_info_`. (This check was

introduced at https://crrev.com/c/2402321/31..32.) But we are planing to

call the member methods from non-single thread task runner for the off

the main thread resource loading project. So this CL changes it to use a

SEQUENCE_CHECKER.



This CL doesn't introduce any behavior change.
